title: For Sale:  Remington Rolling Block Navy Arms in .444 Marlin w/ Ammo, Dies& Brass
postcontent: I have for sale a very nice Navy Arms chambered in .444 Marlin. The gun is in beautiful condition, and works great. The Frame, Breech Block, Hammer and Trigger are all beautifully case hardened steel. The 26" barrel is a really nice piece of machining, as it's 1 1/8" octagon for the first 11", then it steps down to 1 1/16" round and tapers to the muzzle to about 3/4". The bluing is deep, with NO machine marks present. The butt plate, barrel band, trigger guard and frame pin keeper are all polished brass, again with no rough machining lines. The wood looks to be Walnut, and is in 100% condition. The case hardening is probably 95% or better, and the bluing on the barrel is probably at 90%. The only real flaw is the bluing on the top of the barrel by the rear sight is worn, with some flaws in the finish.The gun shoots wonderfully, and it's really a pleasure to shoot as it's quite heavy, so there's no sharp recoil like a lever action .444 Marlin. The rifle weighs over 10 pounds, and feels nice in your hands or at your shoulder. The stock shape has a nice grip and pleasant drop. Also included in the sale is a box of loaded ammunition and spent brass, as well as high-quality .444 diesIf you haven't fired the .444 marlin, it's really a neat round.  Size-wise and overall performance is similar to high-performance 45-70 rounds (for modern firearms, NOT trapdoors), so it can be loaded at fairly high pressures.  The nice part is it uses .429 bullets, the same as the .44 Magnum, .44 special, .44 Russian, etc.  So there is LOT of options out there for projectiles.  Normally the round can have a sharp recoil when loaded to it's potential, but the weight of this rifle keeps that very comfortable.  My 13 year old son shot heavy loads with no problems, and he's a bean pole!We'll have to go through an FFL for this rifle, but I know one in South Mt Vernon that will do it for only $25. Buyer pays transfer fees. I can also ship the rifle, but keep it mind that actual shipping charges will be fairly high due to the rifle's weight.Give me a call if you want to come look. I'm located near Sedro-Woolley in Skagit County.

title: For Sale/Trade:  PRICE DROP - Vortex HS LR 2.5-10x32 FFP - Horus Style MOA reticle
postcontent: I have a Vortex scope, named in the title for sale/trade. A few things about this scope people might not be familiar with due to its similarity to the PST series. 1.The turrets are capped. People freak out about this, but it is due to the reticle design, which is of the Horus type. The reticle is designed to eliminate dialing for both windage and elevation, especially out to long range. This is less busy than most Horus reticles, which means the extra stuff is there when you need it, and you only really notice the main crosshairs when you don't need it. Pic of the reticle subtension below. 2. FFP - meaning that the subtensions are consistent across the whole magnification. This concerns people for short range. I shot a deer at around 40 yards with this on 5X last year in crappy light. Wasn't that hard. 3. MOA instead of MILS. I have shot both, I find that an MOA reticle of the Horus type is extremely useful, especially in a hunting context if you aren't used to thinking in MILs. 4. The PST is illuminated, this is non illuminated. I also think that the reticle is more useful in this scope than any of the PST reticles for wind calls. If they made this scope in MILs and in 4-16 I would have one. But they don't. I believe this scope is most at home on either an SPR or a lighter precision or hunting rig, both of which I have pictured. I purchased this new from Cabelas, it retails for 900 dollars, street price is usually 800 or so, similar to it's slightly different brother the PST. I am selling it because I am interested in precision rifle competition, and want to get a MIL based reticle with more magnification. I will sell for 450 shipped Or I will trade for the below scopes, or scopes similar to them. Vortex PST 4-16 in MILs, either FFP or SFP SWFA 3-15x Vortex HST in 4-16 in MILs. If you have another quality mid range scope in the 3-15 or 4-16 range, that is MIL/MIL, illuminated doesn't hurt, throw it out there.

title: For Sale:  Trijicon ACOG
postcontent:
The TA31RCO is an Advanced Combat Optical Gunsight (ACOG) designed for the US Army's M4 weapon system (14.5" barrel). It incorporates dual illumination technology using a combination of fiber optics and self-luminous tritium. This allows the aiming point to always be illuminated without the use of batteries. The tritium illuminates the aiming point in total darkness, and the fiber optic self-adjusts reticle brightness during daylight according to ambient light conditions. This allows the operator to keep both eyes open while engaging targets and maintaining maximum situational awareness.
Designed to the exact specifications of the United States Marine Corps, the unique reticle pattern provides quick target acquisition at close combat ranges while providing enhanced target identification and hit probability out to 800 meters utilizing the Bullet Drop Compensator.
No tools are needed for windage and elevation adjustments because the TA31RCO features external adjusters, making it waterproof up to 11m without caps.Includes:KillflashCaseACOG coverLens BrushOwner's Manual
